segments.text: April 26, 1986, interview with Henry Tom Heyer, Vietnam veteran, Marine Corps helicopter pilot.
OK, Tom, how did you happen to be in the service?
Were you drafted or volunteered?
Well, after I finished college in August of 1965,
I immediately got an induction notice from the Army.
And knowing that if I was drafted as such, that I wouldn't have any choice as to what my job would be in the service.
And I had also always sort of wanted to fly.
And I thought this might be a good opportunity.
So rather than letting the Army draft me,

I volunteered for the Air Force and I went ahead and took the Air Force entrance exams and the Air Force physical and would have been accepted however they had filled their quota so they wouldn't take me and in the meantime I had gone up for my induction physical and all that and was about to receive

orders to report and I got a phone call from the Marine recruiter and he said that he had access to the Air Force test and the like and that if I would consider being in the Marine Corps that they would try to get me into the air wing and use the Air Force test and the Air Force physical so I wouldn't have to go through all that again.
So I went ahead and joined the Marine Corps.
And actually signed papers in October of 65 and reported for duty in January of 66.
And went through officer's school in Quantico, Virginia in January, February and March of 66.
And then when I received my commission in March of 66, I reported for flight school.
Let's see.
It was in May, May of 66.
In the meantime, I stayed up in Quantico with some other officers waiting for orders to report to flight school.
And got married.
in the meantime also and reported to Pensacola, Florida in May.
I think it was around May the 15th, I'm not really sure about the date, and went through flight school and ended up in helicopters.
There was a division in flight school from, you could go for jets or helicopters and, but
the cutoff for jets was pretty high and didn't quite make it so they went to helicopters and actually ended up in reporting in Vietnam I believe it was Halloween day in 1967 and was in Nam from
October 67 to November 68, during which time was the now famous Tet Offensive.
About where were you stationed, and if more than one place, can you tell us that?
Yeah, when I originally
reported into Vietnam, flew into Da Nang, and from there went to, of course it was just the next day, went to Phu Bai and joined HMM 362 helicopter squadron.
And stayed in Phu Bai, let's see,
until I believe it was about mid-March of 68.

And from Fubai, one aboard ship, I'd get them mixed up whether it was on the Iwo Jima first or the Princeton, but one or the other one aboard ship, the squadron was actually aboard ship until I believe it was about September of 68.
So from March to September we were aboard ship and when we disembarked we went to Marble Mountain which was just outside of Da Nang and operated in the southern part.
I call it the southern, it's still the northern part of South Vietnam but as far as I Corps was concerned it was the southern part.
While operating in Fubai, we had medevac.
It was mainly medevac and CNC.
CNC being command and control.
Also called in the ranks the Ragpicker Express, where you'd go.
I flew the H-34.
It's a Sikorsky, antiquated Sikorsky helicopter.
And it was the last of the reciprocating engine helicopters.
And it was the best bullet bouncer in the world.
It had this big R-18-20 engine sitting right there in front of you for your bullet bouncer.
But we ran
like I said, medevac and CNC.
And the CNC part was we might go to Da Nang and we would fly wing them on a Huey, which would have some kind of brass, a kernel or
very seldom in general, but flying around to different locations, checking on different headquarters and the like.

Pick them up in Da Nang and fly them up to Phu Bai or Quang Tri or Dong Ha, and they would check on operations there with the command, and then fly them back home, and that would be home being Da Nang.
That'd be a full day's operation for us.
And other than that, we would have an occasional recon insert or extract.
But you could probably say the main priority of our squadron was medevac.
Actually, my first flight in country was medevac.
We had, well I was there for I guess maybe two days before I actually did any flying.
And I can't remember the lieutenant's name that I went out with on that first flight, but it was quite a memorable experience in the fact that we went to, we were
operating out of Quang Tri.

Well, of course our squadron was based in Phu Bai, but we would send out different aircraft to different operating areas to run medevac and that day we were running out of Quang Tri and our first evacuation was 16
KIAs and about 20 wounded and it was quite a gruesome awakening for your first flight in country, you know, to think that boy, you know, I hope the hell is not like this the whole 13 months.
Was it all United States people?
Yeah, right.
It was all Marine Corps.
We were, it was strictly Marine Corps in that area.
At that time the Army had not moved in at all.

but that really and truly that was a rude awakening but I can't remember right off the top of my head that we had a worse day after that we had some more some days with more action in them but never had a day where
we evacuated that many KIAs out of one zone.
It was pretty gruesome, where it was.
What was your opinion of the one-year tour of duty for the US soldiers?
Well, at least having a definite time span, you felt like that
you had a target to shoot for and that you were going to come home, versus like in World War II and the like, where people spent years over there.
Stayed in for the duration.
Right, and had no idea when they would be able to come home.
But then again, well, just like reporting for anything the first time,
When you first got there, you had a vague idea because you had indoctrination before you went.
You had a vague idea about how it was going to be.
But starting from day one, it's a learning experience no matter what people tell you.
And you fall into the routine, you get the idea of
what's actually going on, even though you don't really have a real good idea of why you're there.
But you get to know the people in your outfit and what your daily routine is.
And over a period of time, you get more proficient at your job.
Being a helicopter pilot, when I went to Vietnam,
I believe I had like 125 flight hours.
And when you get to 500 flight hours, you are eligible to be a HACC, which is a helicopter aircraft commander.
Prior to that, you're a H2P, which is a helicopter second pilot.
So during those first 500 hours,
You're sitting second seat.
You're learning.
Of course, you definitely have responsibilities and the like, but it's a learning process before you get to the position of 500 hours and being an aircraft commander.
Which takes a while.
I can't remember exactly when I did become a hack.
But let's see, it was probably around in February, making me have been there, what, November, December, January, about four months.
It may have been before that, I don't know.
During this time, you're learning, you're getting proficient at your job.
You're learning the ins and outs of everything.
And then you get to a point to where you are about as proficient as you're going to get at that particular job.
And

Not so much in the case of helicopter pilots, but evidently but occasionally it does happen where you would get a helicopter aircraft commander be drawn out of that particular MOS and being sent to another school to be a forward observer.
And what is MOS?
That's military occupational specialty.
My MOS was helicopter pilot.
Then you had changes of MOS, like just referred to going to a forward observer or whatever.
H2P?
No.
No, H2P is helicopter second pilot.
Yeah, but so during this period of time, the person may be drawn out to be a forward observer, and then that might be a three-month stint, then put back into a squadron.
During that time, well, when you put back in a squadron,

you haven't forgotten how to fly, but you're still going to have another period of learning experience, which knocks off the productivity of the individual because they've been away from their job for a while.
Also, along this line,
with having a specific time span to spend in Vietnam, you lose some proficiency in the fact that after a person gets halfway, they're thinking that it's downhill from then on.
They're looking to go home.
They start being a little more conservative.
The closer you get to going home, the more conservative you get.
In the air wing, we really had it.
It was pretty well understood that you were going to perform the whole way through.
In our squadron, anyway, you flew right up until the last week.
If you made it that far, they'd give you the last week off.
You might have an easy CNC run or something like that, but they'd definitely take you off of medevac.
But then there were definitely some people who just flat, if they were on medevac,
They wouldn't take that extra little edge.
They wouldn't go that extra little bit to try and go in and pick somebody up if the zone was hot.
Even when they were ordered to?
Right.
Of course, it's hard to say that you were ordered to because it was
I'd say 98% of the time, pilot discretion as to whether you would go into an LZ or not, whether you would jeopardize yourself, your machine, and your crew to go in and pick up possibly one person.
Prime cases of this, prime instances,

There were a few times, and I say few because there were definitely more than one, where, and it always seemed to happen on night medevac, you'd get an emergency medevac, go in and pick up the guy, taking all kinds of chances because you'd be, the only thing, the only lighting you would have to go into an LZ would be maybe a heat tab or,
or if you were lucky, a flashlight or something like that.
What's a heat tab?
Okay, a heat tab is a little tablet that, it's a phosphorus-type tablet you would use to heat your C-rations.
And it gives off a small glow.
It's mostly heat, but there is a blue flame to it.
And you can see it a little bit, but not very well from the helicopter.
Okay.
And it's not much of a navigational device.
The heat tabs will be on the ground there.
Right, right.
And so you try to find your LZ with the help of a heat tab and go and pick up somebody like that maybe suffering from a case of malaria.
And like I say, that happened on more than one occasion.
And it's a damn shame that...
You would have to go in at night, especially, risking the crew and the helicopter.
And possibly even, if you missed the zone, crash into some of the troops or something for somebody with a cotton pick in case of malaria.
Actually, we lost one entire crew.
I don't know if the reason for the medevac is lost in my mind right now because of the circumstances that came afterwards.
But we had an entire crew go out on a night medevac, and they were being vectored by the ground control by radar.
And they vectored them right into the side of a mountain.
And we lost the whole crew.
But I don't know, perhaps that night it was a real emergency, a do or die situation for the person on the ground.
Like I say, I don't remember.
But we did lose a complete crew because of that.
Whose fault it was, you really can't say.
But things like that you reflect back on.
How about after the halfway point?
Were there any changes personally in your attitudes or what you did?
Well, a person really doesn't have to admit that maybe they had a little drop in their

enthusiasm about doing their job but I'm sure to a certain extent most everyone has some drop in enthusiasm and like I mentioned before looking forward to that going home date and taking a little bit less of a chance but then again there are
There are others who go for it all the way.
One of the crew, one member of the crew that was killed in that incident I just mentioned was a major, and he was due to go home the next week.
Sort of a sad situation.
He really shouldn't have been on night medevac that night anyway, but I think he volunteered for it.
And that's just one of the breaks of the game.
If you're going to go, you're going to go.
So I guess you might as well put out the whole way.
But it's a strong, what would you say, tendency to protect yourself.
And when you reach the halfway point, you're halfway home.
and halfway home is what you're thinking about.
Were you familiar with defoliation, and did you see any effects of it?

Well, I don't know if you could really, if I could really say that it was actually defoliation or not, but I know when I first got to Vietnam, I was really impressed with how beautiful the countryside was.
It was really lush and green, and no doubt about it, it was a beautiful country.
Later on in my tour of Haiti, and especially towards the end of it, it was quite evident how much effect the war had on the country, just in the 12 to 13 months that I was there.
I believe actually in the area that we were in.
Which area was that?
From Da Nang north.
Da Nang up through Fu Bai, Quang Tri, and Khe Sanh.
All up in that area, the countryside seemed to be just totally pockmarked with B-52 strikes.
It was just devastating how much effect it had on it, just crater after crater.
You mean that would be the effects of rolling thunder?
We weren't familiar with that terminology, but right.
It was really fascinating, though, how beautiful the country was to begin with.
And then after, towards the end, you saw the destruction.
Absolutely.
So you really didn't notice defoliation and the leaves falling off the trees to be able to help you see better on the ground?
No, not really.
Any of the LZs or landing zones that we went into were, of course, I don't know, when you're down there,
In a zone, picking up somebody, you're not really looking at the scenery too terribly much.
It could have been evident in me not noticing it at the time.
The only time I really noticed the countryside was flying at altitude, you know, going from one place to another.
And whether it was actually from defoliation or not, I couldn't say.
Okay, you mentioned earlier flying alongside the Hueys.
Can you describe the differences between the H-34 helicopters you flew and the Hueys?
Well, the H-34, it's an antiquated aircraft.
It's completely retired now, I do believe.
But like I mentioned then, it was a
It had a reciprocating engine versus a jet engine like the Huey has.
What does reciprocating engine mean?
Gasoline piston driven.
Not as powerful?
Pound for pound, much less powerful.
We had a faster reaction time as far as the engine was concerned than a jet.
The Huey, of course, is a much more up-to-date aircraft.
Being jet propelled and the like, it's more maneuverable.
And of course, it has higher technology in it, more sophisticated weaponry and the like.
It's a more stable platform for the weaponry.
The H-34, we had a crew of the pilot, co-pilot, crew chief, and a gunner.
And when we had medevac, we also had a corpsman aboard.
The crew chief and the gunner both had M60 machine guns.
It's a .30 caliber machine gun.
And mounted in the windows.
And crew chief on one side, gunner on the other, so they could cover both sides of the aircraft.
Of course, the Huey, they were much more versatile than the fact that some of them had rocket pods.
Some of them had a Gatling gun.
The Huey Cobra gunship.
It had the whole smear.
It was a two-man army right there.
Our squadron was strictly H-34s, what you would call a utility squadron, I guess, in the fact that we did a little bit of everything, but we were not an arsenal.
We had no firepower.
We had the two M60s for defense, and that was it.
We were there for extracting the wounded.
We put in some recon patrols.
We would take out some recon patrols.
But it was strictly plain vanilla as far as the aircraft was concerned.
What was your opinion of the Vietnamese, such as the South Vietnamese, North Vietnamese, and the Viet Cong, and any contact you had with them?
How did you view them?
Did you view them as humans?
How did you look at them?
Well, my contact with the Vietnamese of any sort was very limited.
We had hooch maids, like I imagine most servicemen did over there, by the fact that there were six or eight of us living in one little old built-up shack, which we called Hooch's.
And I believe
I believe the fee for a hooch made was somewhere around $30 a month.
I'm not sure, but I believe that sort of rings a bell.
So you divide that up with five or six people, and it's pretty cheap to get your...
The building swept out every day, and they'd polish your boots, and they'd do your washing and stuff like that.
So it was quite reasonable.
And that was really the only contact that I had with the Vietnamese...

actually on a person to person type basis and those women really well they didn't speak English to begin with I really didn't have any desire to try to carry on any kind of a conversation with them anyway and so that was really about the extent of my
contact with the Vietnamese as such.
In observing, though, we would fly in from place to place and land in from place to place.
And going to the exchange in Da Nang, where we did our shopping for various sundry items, there were some Vietnamese around there.
The kids might come up to you a little bit, just like they do in Mexico, wanting something for nothing.
But from stories that I heard prior, it was best to leave them alone.
And if you could at all do it in any way at all, you had to avoid them.

Cotton picking kids coming up with grenades in their hands and stuff like that and just booby trapping you or throwing one in the helicopter while you're sitting there waiting for somebody else to come along.
And it, for all practical purposes, you wanted to stay away from it.
As a people, I would say they were very, very backward type people.
I would say probably upwards of 80% of the people.
It seemed like everywhere we were, anyway, that maybe we were just coming in contact or observing the downtrodden portion of them.
But I'm sure that the Vietnamese people as a whole were downtrodden.
But one thing really strikes me, a couple of things, actually.
as to the type of people that they were.
The women, they'd be out in the field gathering rice or gathering firewood or whatever for their little cook fires and stuff.
And if they had to go to the bathroom, it was amazing.
You know, they wore the black pajamas and all that, the silken type pajamas.
And they'd just roll up their leg, the leg of the pajamas, and pull it over the side and stand up and pee.
Just like a cow pissing on a flat rock is amazing.
You know, you can't have any respect for people that do that kind of thing.
How about taking a crab?
Well, they had a morning ritual.
Actually, the only time I observed it was after we were off ship and we were based at Marble Mountain.
And Marble Mountain is right outside of Da Nang, so it's a pretty heavily populated area.
And early in the morning, around between 7 and 8, you'd fly around to the north of Da Nang
And Da Nang was actually a harbor city, or I guess you'd call it a city.
And the northern beach was commonly called Shit Beach.
You'd fly there between 7 and 8 o'clock in the morning, and that's when everybody gets up.
And they go out there, and they take a crap out there right in the tidal waters.
Men and women?
Men and women, kids, everybody.
And they'd just be lined up along the beach, taking a crap out there in about a foot of water and expecting the tide to take it out.
And I guess it did, because they kept on doing it.
It was amazing.
So, you know, what kind of people are you talking about?
So, you know, did the people ever even, were they aware of...
of what was going on in their country.
People like that are not well-informed.
They don't know politics.
I'm sure they were aware that their whole country has been a war-torn country for as long as they can remember and generations back, but they don't know why.
Probably didn't care.
They don't care.
If they had their fish and their rice for three meals a day or two meals a day, they'd be perfectly satisfied.
So how about, how did you view them as a human being?
Let's say, if you would have seen a dead gook laying there and also a dead American, did you make a distinction between, well, that's a dead person, American,
And that's just a gook.
What was the distinction?
Did you look at him as a human being or not?
Well, yes, I did.
I think that anything that has two legs and stands upright and can carry on a conversation, no matter how deep that conversation can be as a human being, and it's a damn shame that

things like that do go on in the world and the the really sad part about it is that it's no matter who tries how hard it's going to go in go on in the world until the end of time okay when you flew medevac what effect
did, seeing all the death and destruction of US soldiers, what effect did that have on you?
And how did you deal with it?
Well, it has to have an effect on anyone, I'm sure.
How much you let it affect you is another thing.

I think I can consider myself as lucky as being one of the kind of people, I don't think I'm a hard person, really and truly I think I'm a pretty soft-hearted person, but something like that, I was fortunate enough to be able to somewhat disconnect myself from, and I think it
He had a lot to do with my first flight in country, which I was relating to earlier.
I wish I could remember the man's name that I flew with that day, but when we extracted the 16 KIAs from one LZ and all the wounded and everything.
During which time, of course, the H-34 only has
capacity of lifting about 12 fully laden combat troops.
So we had to make a number of trips in to make this many extracts, or extract this many people.
And during which time, we had to refuel.
And so we went into Dong Ha to refuel.
And we were sitting there refueling, and this pilot was sitting there, and he looked over at me and just started laughing, and he started cracking jokes.
And I was puzzled by what he was doing, and later he told me that the only way that he could cope with what he was doing out there and seeing what he was seeing was to...

lighten up and take his mind off of it and think about something else crack a joke or anything and I can't remember what his worries were that's a number of years ago but it hung with me and I think me being with him during that first date of first day of turmoil and tragedy that I saw
prepared me for the rest of the year.
And it let me shrug off some of this, detach myself from it, and not get personally involved.
There was one fellow that I did go through.
I went through OCS with him.
I went through flight school with him.
And when we went to Vietnam, we were assigned to different squadrons.
He really let it get to him.
And during his year over there, he probably lost about 40 pounds by worrying about it.
And he lived through it.
I don't know how he is now.
I haven't seen him since then.
But he was an absolute nervous wreck.
There are many, many tales, as you see on TV every now and then.
They bring up another tale about Vietnam and all this, personal interviews and the like.

where so many people have let things get to them, and blaming society and thinking that the US government and the US people owe them a life and a well-being for the rest of their days, which I totally disagree with.
A person goes over there to do a job,
And like, I would have been drafted, but I did volunteer.
And anyone that's in any service besides the Army is a volunteer.
And a lot of the ones in the Army are volunteers.
And you're there to defend your country no matter what the politicians
how bad they screwed up, or whatever.
You're there to defend your country, you're there to do the job for your country, and you're laying your life on the line for yourself, your country, your kids, your family in the future.
But did you ever question why you were doing what you were doing?
Why they were making you do this?
I never have been much of a person to be involved in politics and not that it would matter anyway.
It would probably just have pissed me off even more to where maybe I would have been more adamant about the situation.
Maybe it was just the way I was raised.
You do your stint for your country, and you do the best you can.
And if you lose a part of your body doing it, then that's the way it happens.
Luckily, I didn't lose anything.
I had a couple of holes in me, but I didn't lose anything.
And I don't feel like...
the U.S. government or the American people or society as a whole owes me a thing.
I did my job, and that was it.
Like I say, maybe it's the way I was raised, brought up, thankful to my mother and father that I could detach myself from the horror and tragedy that was going on over there.
And I'll also credit some to the pilot that I was with.
Not having, you know, I didn't let it affect me mentally.
Okay, why don't you describe when you were wounded?
Okay, let's see.
At the time, we were, the squadron was based aboard ship
I don't remember if it was the Iwo Jima or the Princeton, but we were on a CMC mission into the northern area up around Da Nang and Khe Sanh area, I mean, pardon me, Dong Ha in the Khe Sanh area.
And about halfway between Dong Ha and Khe Sanh,
was an LZ, totally secure LZ, called Camp Carol.
And it later changed its name, I don't remember what to.
But we had been running the Rag Picker Express that day.
Anybody that was being transferred from one unit to another or new people coming in or what have you,
taken from maybe Quang Tri to Dong Han and then to Camp Carroll or Khe Sanh or whatever.
And there had been a call that a recon patrol had come into Camp Carroll and they needed transportation back to Quang Tri.

So we always flew in twos and I was helicopter commander at the time and we were flying the second helicopter so we weren't the point men and we were sitting in the LZ waiting to pick up this recon patrol.
We had radio communication with the people on the ground and

uh they were trying to locate this recon patrol that needed the transportation and we sat there i guess it seemed like forever but it was probably around 10 minutes they were trying to locate this recon patrol and couldn't find them couldn't find them and finally they
found out that they had been picked up by someone else and already taken so we asked them if they needed anybody else or if anybody else there needed any transportation and they said well no
